<section>
  <title>Exploration 1, due February 1</title>
<handout xml:id="exp-1" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Exploration 1, due February 1</title>
      <p>
        Make sure to familariaze yourself with the Exploration <xref ref="instructions" text="custom"> Instructions </xref> found on the home page.
      </p>
    <problem> 
        <task workspace="0.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Choose two <xref ref="random" text="custom">random</xref> vectors <m>\vec v, \vec w</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> which are not multiples of each other.
            </p>
            
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Choose a random third vector <m> \vec b </m> in <m> \mathbb{R}^2</m> and express <m>\vec b</m> as a linear combination of <m>\vec v, \vec w</m>; that is, find weights <m> c_1, c_2 \in \mathbb{R}</m> such that <md> c_1\vec v + c_2 \vec w = \vec b</md>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task workspace="true">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Sketch the vectors <m>\vec v, \vec w, \vec b</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> and show, geometrically, how the linear combination from (b) makes sense.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
    </problem>
    <problem>
      <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Now, choose two random vectors <m>\vec v, \vec w</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> which are not multiples of each other. Can every vector <m>\vec b \in \mathbb{R}^3</m> be expressed as a linear combination of <m>\vec v, \vec w</m>? Justify your answer.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Choose a random third vector <m> \vec b \mathbb{R}^3</m> that can be expressed as a linear combination of <m>\vec v, \vec w</m>. Find appropriate weights <m> c_1, c_2 \in \mathbb{R}</m> such that <md> c_1\vec v + c_2 \vec w = \vec b</md>
            </p>
          </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="true">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <em>Bonus (Not graded)</em>: Sketch the vectors <m>\vec v, \vec w, \vec b</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> and show, geometrically, how the linear combination from (b) makes sense.
            </p>
          </statement>
      </task>
    </problem>

  
  
</handout>
